revision.text:
[[Image:Invention of the Typewriter.jpg|thumb|300px|right|Wisconsin Historical Marker]]

'''Carlos Glidden''' (November 8, 1834 &ndash; March 11, 1877),<ref>Koichi and Motoko Yasuoka: Myth of QWERTY Keyboard, NTT Publishing, Tokyo (2008).</ref> along with [[Christopher Sholes]], [[Frank Haven Hall]], and [[Samuel W. Soule]], invented the first practical [[typewriter]] at a machine shop in [[Milwaukee, Wisconsin|Milwaukee]], [[Wisconsin]].<ref>[http://www.wisconsinhistory.org/dictionary/index.asp?action=view&term_id=12319&term_type_id=2&term_type_text=Places&letter=I Invention of the Typewriter], Wisconsin Historical Marker'', Retrieved May 11, 2008.</ref><ref>[http://www.wisconsinhistory.org/dictionary/index.asp?action=view&term_id=1307&keyword=glidden Carlos Glidden]</ref> He kept on improving the typewriter until he died.<ref>Carlos Glidden: The New Type Writer,[http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=chi.70756375;seq=448 Scientific American, 27(9), p.132 (1872).]</ref><ref>U. S. Patents Nos. 200351 &amp; 470784.</ref>

